Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Take the @British beef mince{500%g} out of
your fridge ~{30%mins} before cooking, if possible. Cut the @red onion{3} in
half lengthways through the root, then peel and slice widthways very thinly
into half moons.

Wash the @potato{2} but don't peel it. Chop the potato lengthways into wedges
the thickness of a thumb. Toss the wedges in @oil{2%tbsp}, lay them out in one
layer spaced apart on a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle over @salt{1/2%tsp} and a good
grind of @pepper{} and cook on the top shelf of your oven for ~{25%minutes}, until
soft inside and brown on the outside.

Heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #saucepan{} on low heat and add the onion with a
pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Add the @balsamic vinegar{1.5%tbsp},
place a lid on the pan and gently cook for ~{20%minutes}, stirring once in a
while.

Mix the beef mince in a #bowl{} with the @ras-el-hanout{1} and @salt{1/2%tsp}.
Form the beef into four equal-sized burger patties.

> Don't press the meat together too firmly, as this will make the texture of your
> burger tough.

Heat @oil{2%tbsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium heat and once hot
gently lay in your burgers. Cook for around ~{5-6%minutes} on each side and
turn them only once. If you want to cook your burgers a little more in the
middle, you can place them in your oven for a few minutes after frying.

Toast the @wholemeal pita{4} for a few minutes then split them in half.

> Sandwich your burgers between the pita bread. If you want to go pita free you
> can always freeze them for another meal.

Serve your burgers with a spoonful of red onions, a spoonful of
@Greek style yoghurt{1}, your potato wedges and the @baby spinach{2}(leaves).

> We left our leaves undressed to balance against the richness of the burger.